SIMPLE: saturate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Saturate
<hw>Sat"u*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Saturated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Saturating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>saturatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>saturare</ets> to saturate, fr.
<ets>satur</ets> full of food, sated. See <er>Satire</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to become completely penetrated, impregnated,
or soaked; to fill fully; to sate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Innumerable flocks and herds covered that vast expanse of emerald
meadow <qex>saturated</qex> with the moisture of the Atlantic.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fill and <qex>saturate</qex> each kind⟦br⟧
With good according to its mind.</q> <rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To satisfy the affinity of; to
cause to become inert by chemical combination with all that it can hold;
<as>as, to <ex>saturate</ex> phosphorus with chlorine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saturate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Saturate
<hw>Sat"u*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>p. a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>saturatus</ets>, p. p.]</ety> <def>Filled to repletion; saturated;
soaked.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dries his feathers <qex>saturate</qex> with dew.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sand beneath our feet is <qex>saturate</qex>⟦br⟧
With blood of martyrs.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saturated</ent>⟦br⟧
